This kind of surprised me. When I was actually playing this game, I had no idea why Black had made this move, but now that I think about it, probably the Rook had been moved in this manner because Black had predicted Qg7+ and wanted to threaten my queen in addition to protecting that row.

Preparing for mate. At this point, the best move for Black would have been Qe8, so that my potential mate would be blocked. (so that when I did Qg8+ followed by Qf7+, he could recapture my queen with his queen, prompting me to take his queen with my knight, which would have then given him my knight and reduced my advantage.
